<HEADLINE>
<P>
NURSING CRISIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to the editorial "Curing the Nurse Shortage" (Dec. 29), I disagree 
with the "experts who prepared the constructive report for the U.S. Department 
of Health Services." 
</P>
<P>
The commission's finding that the "money matters most" is wrong. The fact is 
that money cannot replace the decrease in a caring attitude toward patients. 
However, in addition to the change in attitude, it is important that nurses 
have "professional recognition, representation on policy-making, regulatory and 
accreditation boards, and the use of a more collaborative approach between 
nurses and other health professionals and the management." 
</P>
<P>
The hot-line effort to inform men and women about nursing career opportunities 
should include one very important question: Does the person, who is inquiring, 
really understand the meaning of the four-letter word care? 
</P>
<P>
ESTHER KAHAN 
</P>
<P>
Rolling Hills Estates 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
