<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
California's economy will again grow faster than the rest of the country in 
1989, aggravating the state's transportation and housing problems, Bank of 
America said in its annual state economic forecast. California's real gross 
state product will grow 3.5% in 1989, said Frederick Cannon, vice president and 
senior economist at the bank. Although that is slower than the 4.8% growth 
expected in 1988 and the 6.2% growth in 1987, it will be 0.7% faster than the 
U.S. real gross national product, Cannon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
CALIFORNIA -- ECONOMY; ECONOMIC FORECASTS; BANK OF AMERICA; HOUSING -- 
CALIFORNIA; CALIFORNIA -- TRANSPORTATION 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011089-0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 3472 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 10, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part 4; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
77 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., which has agreed to plead guilty to six felonies 
to avoid an indictment for financial fraud, said a deadline set for today for 
reaching agreement with the SEC had been dropped. "These discussions are still 
under way," a Drexel spokesman said, adding that a settlement is still 
expected. As part of the plea-bargaining agreement with the U.S. Attorney's 
Office in Manhattan, Drexel must resolve a massive suit brought by the SEC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
