<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Women who drink beverages with caffeine may take longer to become pregnant, say 
scientists at the National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences in 
Research Triangle Park, N.C. The study was published in December in The Lancet, 
a British medical journal. A group of 104 women planning to become pregnant 
provided data on the amount of caffeinated beverages they consumed during the 
time they tried to conceive, the study said. Women who drank more than one cup 
of caffeinated coffee a day, or the equivalent in tea and colas, took 
significantly longer to become pregnant than women who drank less. "Our data 
suggests that it is the women's current caffeine consumption, not her past 
habits, that affects her fertility," said Dr. Allen J. Wilcox, principal 
investigator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
