<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE PREPS; 
</P>
<P>
GIRLS' ATHLETE OF THE WEEK; 
</P>
<P>
OUTSIDE MOVE HELPS PUT POLISH ON ERKENBRACK'S GAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DONNA CARTER, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For 3 years, 5-foot 11-inch, 140-pound Keri Erkenbrack of Canyon High School 
posted up near the paint, her little elbows ready to do battle with the biggest 
of Orange County's centers. 
</P>
<P>
But this season, Canyon Coach Bill Fitzgibbons moved her to forward, and 
Erkenbrack is beginning to shine after 3 years of being the diamond that was 
roughed up. 
</P>
<P>
Erkenbrack, The Times' athlete of the week, scored a career-high 31 points and 
pulled down 10 rebounds in a 63-37 victory over El Modena Thursday in the 
Century League opener for both teams. 
</P>
<P>
Two days earlier, she scored 25 points in Canyon's 70-24 nonleague victory over 
Troy. 
</P>
<P>
Erkenbrack leads her team in scoring with 20.3 points per game and rebounding 
(10.4). She also has been the soccer team's starting goalie for 3 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
Playing center, Erkenbrack was used to taking a lot of shots -- inside. She had 
to be persuaded to shoot from the perimeter when she was moved to forward 
during summer-league play, Fitzgibbons said. 
</P>
<P>
But after working over the summer at practice and in the La Mirada High School 
summer league, Erkenbrack is comfortable with 20-foot shots and is the team's 
leading 3-point shooter. 
</P>
<P>
"It was a big transition," Erkenbrack said. 
</P>
<P>
"Inside, I'm only 5-11 and I'm used to getting killed underneath. I have to 
really fight for position. Outside, I have an advantage with my height. And 
having experience playing inside, I can always drive to the basket or post up." 
</P>
<P>
Fitzgibbons acknowledges that Erkenbrack's scoring average could soar in a 
program with less of a team focus. 
</P>
<P>
Two other starters average about 9 points per game -- point guard Christa 
Ramirez and 6-3 center Sheri Rhyne, whose arrival has freed Erkenbrack to roam 
the perimeter. 
</P>
<P>
"Keri is not the focal point," Fitzgibbons said. "Her main objective is to play 
good defense and hit the boards. She doesn't have to lead our team." 
</P>
<P>
TOP PERFORMER 
</P>
<P>
Amy Jalewalia scored 70 points in 2 Garden Grove League games, including 45 
points in a 66-28 victory over Kennedy Friday. In that victory, she pulled down 
21 rebounds and had 14 steals. She scored 25 points and had 13 rebounds in a 
67-48 victory over Rancho Alamitos Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Keri Erkenbrack 
</P>
<P>
Canyon High School 
</P>
<P>
Position: Forward 
</P>
<P>
Height, Class: 5-11, Senior 
</P>
<P>
Last Week: Scored 31 points in a 63-37 victory over El Modena and scored 25 
points in a 70-24 victory over Troy. 
</P>
<P>
Season: Erkenbrack leads Canyon in scoring (20.4 points per game) and 
rebounding (10.4 per game). 
</P>
</TEXT>
