<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
BANK TO PAY $14 MILLION FOR BIAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Chicago bank that was the government's biggest target of racial and sexual 
discrimination charges has agreed to pay $14 million in back pay, the largest 
such settlement ever obtained by the federal government, the Labor Department 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
The settlement also requires the Harris Trust and Savings Bank to revise its 
affirmative action policies, provide training and other assistance to women and 
minority workers and file periodic reports with the government documenting its 
compliance with anti-discrimination laws. It was not immediately clear how many 
current or former bank employees would share the award. 
</P>
</TEXT>
